etymologies: early 17th century; earliest use found in Michael Drayton (1536–1631), poet. From trans- + classical Latin lūna moon + -ary, after lunary and sublunary

definitions: Existing or situated beyond or above the moon, or beyond the orbit or (supposed) sphere of the moon (now chiefly historical). Also figurative: heavenly or otherworldly in nature or origin; spiritual, visionary.
